# Project standards

Apply to all work in this repository unless a scoped rule overrides.

## Layout

- `backend/` — NestJS + TypeORM API (layered architecture).
- `frontend/` — Next.js 14 App Router app (React 18, TypeScript).
- `docker-compose.yml` brings up Postgres + backend + frontend.

## Naming

- Use descriptive names. Avoid single-letter identifiers (i, j, x) except in trivial math.
- Loop indices should be readable (`index`, `artifactIndex`).
- Prefer clarity over brevity.

## Architecture

- Minimize scope: smallest correct diff; do not change unrelated code.
- Reuse existing patterns and the dedicated layer/folder for each concern.
- Do not over-engineer abstractions for one-off use.
- Keep the in-process model intact: SSE notifications run over the in-process
  `@nestjs/event-emitter` bus. Do not reintroduce Redis or extra infra without
  being asked.

## API response shape

- The backend wraps every success in `{ status, statusCode, message, entity }`
  via the global `ResponseInterceptor`.
- Errors are normalized by `AllExceptionsFilter` to
  `{ statusCode, message, path, timestamp }`.
- Raw/streaming endpoints (e.g. SSE) must opt out of the success wrapper with
  `@SkipSuccessWrapper()`.
- The frontend unwraps `entity` centrally in `lib/api.ts` (`handle`); keep new
  calls going through that helper.

## Auth

- The only protection is `ApiKeyGuard` (shared secret via the `x-api-key`
  header), applied to write endpoints with `@UseGuards(ApiKeyGuard)`. There is
  no JWT/RBAC; read endpoints are public.

## After writing code

- Backend: `cd backend && npm run build` and `npm test`.
- Frontend: `cd frontend && npm run build` (and `npm run lint`).
- Only create git commits when the user explicitly asks.
